
[1]continual

   CONTINUAL, a. [L. See Continue.]

   1. Proceeding without interruption or cessation; unceasing; not
   intermitting; used in reference to time.

   He that hath a merry heart hath a continual feast. Proverbs 15.

   I have great heaviness and continual sorrow of heart. Romans 9.

   2. Very frequent; often repeated; as, the charitable man has continual
   application for alms.

   3. Continual fever, or continued fever, a fever that abates, but never
   entirely intermits, till it comes to a crisis; thus distinguished from
   remitting and intermitting fever.

   4. Continual claim, in law, a claim that is made from time to time
   within every year or day, to land or other estate, the possession of
   which cannot be obtained without hazard.

   5. Perpetual.
